ith Capesthorne Hall, near Macclesfield."],"variants":[{"name":"Devenport","meanings":["English and Irish (Lancashire): variant of   Davenport  . The spelling <b>Devonport</b> is found in Ireland and it may have been this form which gave rise to <i>Devenport</i>."]},{"name":"Dunworth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Eamon, Niall.","Irish: adopted in Ireland by bearers of Gaelic <b>Ó Donndubhartaigh</b> (see   Davenport   2).","English: perhaps a variant of <b>Dungworth</b>, see   Dunsworth  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Davenport was born in 1270, in Davenport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with William de Bulkeley. She died in 1326, in her hometown, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1270–1326":"1270–1326","1265–1310":"1265–1310","1297–1350":"1297–1350","1326":"1326","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","1297":"1297","1350":"1350","1270":"1270","Davenport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Davenport, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bulkeley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bulkeley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Eaton, Cheshire, England":"Eaton, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"